PrimeDAO, Block Science , Commons Stack and other projects have been involved in it. There are examples of one org being a member of a DAO, in this case there is usually an individual representative that would be responsible for participating in decisions there. 
The direction you can take will depend on how decentralized you wish those orgs to be. 
So, would you want centralized orgs to collaborate with each other in a decentralized way? Or decentralized org to collaborate in a decentralized way? 
The later is definitely more complex but could have very interesting results
In this particular case it would be a group of traditional (centralized) nonprofits,  some of which already have a relationship as “sister organizations”
And then they would share a common treasury?
Yes the major use case is a shared, self-executing common treasury that could work internationally
So maybe 50 percent goes to periodic funding injections equally across organizations, 30 toward special projects the member orgs vote on, 20 as emergency funds in case one member org is in trouble
So that’s a “simple” DAO. The main challenge you will have is making sure all the people from the centralized orgs are aligned on the decisions they will make for the shared treasury
